Function to determine top metabolites for each variable

get_top_metabolites <- function(data, variable_columns, num_top_metabolites = 10) {
  dat = data[, variable_columns]
  dat1 = apply(dat, 1, function(x) scale(x))
  top_metabolites_indices = apply(dat1, 1, function(x) order(x, decreasing = TRUE)[1:num_top_metabolites])
  top_metabolites = rownames(dat)[top_metabolites_indices]
  return(top_metabolites)
}

# Determine top metabolites for the entire dataset
top_metabolites_all = get_top_metabolites(Brown_adipose_2022, 2:49)
# Determine top metabolites for each variable
top_metabolites_IBA = get_top_metabolites(Brown_adipose_2022, 2:9)
top_metabolites_MAR = get_top_metabolites(Brown_adipose_2022, 10:17)
top_metabolites_OCT = get_top_metabolites(Brown_adipose_2022, 18:26)
top_metabolites_SEP = get_top_metabolites(Brown_adipose_2022, 27:35)
top_metabolites_TOR = get_top_metabolites(Brown_adipose_2022, 36:49)

# Print the top metabolites
print(top_metabolites_all)

Tip: instead of overwriting the data each time when you segment the data, just save them as separate objects. Also, make the data wrangling part into a function. This will clean up the code a lot.

Separate the data into segments

dat.IBA=dat=Brown_adipose_2022[,2:9] 
dat.MAR=dat=Brown_adipose_2022[,10:17] 
dat.OCT=dat=Brown_adipose_2022[,18:26] 
dat.SEP=dat=Brown_adipose_2022[,27:35] 
dat.TOR=dat=Brown_adipose_2022[,36:49]

Make a function to reorganize the data

dat_for_heatmap=function(x) {
  dat.scale=apply(dat,1,function(x) scale(x))
  features=data.frame(Feature=Brown_adipose_2022[,1]) 
  dat3=cbind(features, t(dat.scale)) 
  dat_pivot=pivot_longer(dat3, -Feature)
  dat_pivot
}

Then, you can just use that within the ggplot function. This way, you can make the different heatmaps by just changing the dataset you input (i.e., you just need to change three letters).

Heres for IBA

ggplot(data = dat_for_heatmap(dat.IBA), aes(x = name, y = Feature, fill = value)) + 
  geom_tile() + 
  scale_fill_gradient2(midpoint = 0, low = "blue", mid = "black", high = "red") + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  labs(title = "Heatmap") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 48, hjust = 1)) + 
  theme(axis.text.y=element_blank(), axis.text.x=element_blank())

and for MAR

ggplot(data = dat_for_heatmap(dat.MAR), aes(x = name, y = Feature, fill = value)) + 
  geom_tile() + 
  scale_fill_gradient2(midpoint = 0, low = "blue", mid = "black", high = "red") + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  labs(title = "Heatmap") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 48, hjust = 1)) + 
  theme(axis.text.y=element_blank(), axis.text.x=element_blank())
